        <!-- Deeper Analysis -->
        <section class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="section-title">Deeper Analysis</h2>
            <div class="space-y-6">
                <div class="card bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md">
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl mb-2 text-gray-800">Operating Margin Drivers</h3>
                    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                        <li><strong>Lower Raw Material Costs:</strong> Cost of materials consumed fell from 42.4% to 36.3% of revenue YoY, driven by lower crude oil prices.</li>
                        <li><strong>Improved Product Margins:</strong> Favorable margins in domestic fuel retail (Jio-bp) and better transportation fuel cracks boosted O2C profitability.</li>
                        <li><strong>Operating Leverage in Consumer Businesses:</strong> Jio's EBITDA margin expanded by 210 bps and Retail's by 20 bps YoY due to scale and efficiency gains.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="card bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md">
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl mb-2 text-gray-800">Working Capital Analysis</h3>
                     <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
                        <div class="bg-green-50 border-l-4 border-green-500 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-800">Positive Signal: Inventory</h4>
                            <p class="text-green-700">Inventory Turnover ratio improved, and the company sold more than it produced, indicating efficient inventory management and a positive cash flow impact.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-500 p-4 rounded-r-lg">
                            <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-800">Potential Red Flag: Receivables</h4>
                            <p class="text-red-700">Debtors Turnover ratio decreased, suggesting it's taking longer to collect cash from customers, which could strain working capital if not managed.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="card bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md">
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl mb-2 text-gray-800">Critique of Management Commentary</h3>
                    <p class="mb-3 text-gray-700">The commentary is broadly consistent with strong YoY results but contains selective framing:</p>
                    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                        <li><strong>Downplaying One-Off Gain:</strong> The record 76.5% PAT growth is heavily inflated by a non-operational gain of ₹8,924 crore, which is not highlighted in the commentary.</li>
                        <li><strong>Ignoring QoQ Revenue Decline:</strong> The 5.2% sequential dip in revenue, a key metric, is completely omitted from the narrative.</li>
                        <li><strong>Selective O2C Narrative:</strong> Focuses on EBITDA growth while ignoring the 1.5% YoY revenue decline and 3.5% drop in production throughput for the O2C segment.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>
        
        <!-- Strategic Outlook -->
        <section>
            <h2 class="section-title">Strategic Outlook: A Competitor's View</h2>
            <div class="space-y-6">
                <div class="card bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md">
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl mb-2 text-blue-800">The Biggest Strategic Opportunity</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">The transition of Jio from a connectivity provider to a high-margin digital life platform. With Digital Services' EBITDA now surpassing the O2C segment, the path is clear to monetize their vast user base by layering financial, cloud, and AI services at near-zero customer acquisition cost, effectively becoming the OS for a digital India.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="card bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md">
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl mb-2 text-red-800">The Most Significant Non-Obvious Risk</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">Regulatory backlash against their "Walled Garden" strategy. The deep integration of services (telecom, media, retail) makes them a prime target for CCI scrutiny. The risk of mandated interoperability, restrictions on bundling, or data-use limitations could strike at the heart of their synergistic model.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="card bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md">
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl mb-2 text-purple-800">Capital Expenditure Priorities</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">The massive Capex of ₹29,875 crore this quarter signals a clear "twin transition" strategy. The largest bets are on <strong>Digital Dominance</strong> (completing the 5G rollout and scaling home broadband) and <strong>Energy Transformation</strong> (building the green energy giga-scale ecosystem), positioning RIL to be the backbone of both India's digital and green economies.</p>
                </div>
                 <div class="card bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-500 p-6 rounded-r-lg">
                    <h3 class="font-bold text-xl mb-2 text-blue-900">The Story of the Quarter</h3>
                    <p class="text-blue-800 leading-relaxed">This report tells a story of a <strong>strategic pivot from a legacy industrial giant into a formidable consumer-technology fortress.</strong> It demonstrates that new growth engines, Digital Services and Retail, are now the primary drivers of profitability. The narrative is one of calculated aggression—using massive cash flows from the legacy business to fund a capital-intensive expansion that aims to create insurmountable moats in the high-growth sectors that will define India's next decade. It is a story not of simple growth, but of <strong>accelerating dominance and the consolidation of market power.</strong></p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Footer Note -->
        <footer class="text-center mt-12">
